## `test_committed_writes_present_after_crash(crashable_db)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-crash-3 -->
<!-- trace: skipped -->
<!-- trace_skip_reason: subprocess + SIGKILL sequence. -->

### Purpose
Any write that returned success to its caller must be visible after reopen. SQLite WAL with `synchronous=FULL` guarantees this.

### Postconditions

```python
crashable_db.spawn()
crashable_db.send("write /committed.txt hello")   # returns success
crashable_db.send("ack")                           # synchronizes with the worker
crashable_db.sigkill()

fs = crashable_db.reopen()
with fs.as_user(0, 0):
    fd = fs.open("/committed.txt", flags=0)
    assert fs.read(fd, size=100, offset=0) == b"hello"
    fs.close_fd(fd)
fs.close()
```

---

## `test_uncommitted_writes_absent_after_crash(crashable_db)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-crash-4 -->
<!-- trace: skipped -->
<!-- trace_skip_reason: subprocess + SIGKILL sequence. -->

### Purpose
A write that was in progress when SIGKILL fired — but had not returned success — must be either fully present or fully absent, never partially present. This is the atomicity half of the durability contract.

### Postconditions

```python
crashable_db.spawn()
# Queue a write but DON'T wait for ack — SIGKILL may arrive before commit.
crashable_db.send("write /maybe.txt " + "x" * 10_000_000, wait_ack=False)
time.sleep(0.01)   # race the daemon
crashable_db.sigkill()

fs = crashable_db.reopen()
with fs.as_user(0, 0):
    if fs.exists("/maybe.txt"):
        # Present: must be exactly 10M bytes. No partial state.
        assert fs.stat("/maybe.txt").size == 10_000_000
    # If absent, that's also acceptable — the write never committed.
fs.close()
```

---

## `test_rename_atomic_under_crash(crashable_db)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-crash-5 -->
<!-- trace: skipped -->
<!-- trace_skip_reason: subprocess + SIGKILL sequence. Rename atomicity under commit IS traceable (test_rename), the crash part is not. -->

### Purpose
`rename(src, dst)` commits in a single SQLite transaction. Post-crash, exactly one of `{src, dst}` exists — never both, never neither.

### Postconditions

```python
crashable_db.spawn()
crashable_db.send("write /src content")
crashable_db.send("ack")
crashable_db.send("rename /src /dst", wait_ack=False)
time.sleep(0.01)
crashable_db.sigkill()

fs = crashable_db.reopen()
with fs.as_user(0, 0):
    src_exists = fs.exists("/src")
    dst_exists = fs.exists("/dst")
    # Exactly one, not both, not neither.
    assert (src_exists, dst_exists) in [(True, False), (False, True)]
    # The content is intact at whichever name won.
    path = "/src" if src_exists else "/dst"
    fd = fs.open(path, flags=0)
    assert fs.read(fd, size=100, offset=0) == b"content"
    fs.close_fd(fd)
fs.close()
```

---

## `test_remount_idempotent(crashable_db)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-crash-6 -->
<!-- trace: skipped -->
<!-- trace_skip_reason: subprocess + SIGKILL sequence. -->

### Purpose
Mounting the same DB twice after a crash (without clean shutdown) must succeed both times. No stale WAL/SHM state should leak across mount attempts.

### Postconditions

```python
crashable_db.spawn()
crashable_db.send("write /x hello")
crashable_db.sigkill()

fs1 = crashable_db.reopen()
with fs1.as_user(0, 0):
    assert fs1.exists("/x")
fs1.close()

# Second remount on same DB.
fs2 = crashable_db.reopen()
with fs2.as_user(0, 0):
    assert fs2.exists("/x")
fs2.close()
```

